liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Karen Mundine, Reconciliation Australia's CEO, was impressed by the prime minister's speech. Speaking to reporter Isabella Tolhurst, Ms Mundine said the proposed Voice to Parliament would make a massive impact on Australia's reconciliation journey. "There is a real commitment, a commitment that it will happen, and that's further than we've ever gotten with this discussion in over a decade." Ms Mundine said the prime minister's speech will act as a push for campaigners to stay the pace, despite negativity surrounding the debate. "We've been conscious of negative feedback that we've received. But it is about change. And change sometimes comes at a cost. But nevertheless, it's not the reason not to do these things," she said. "I think moments like [the prime minister's speech] gives hope to everyone that believes this is the right thing to do. And it gives them a little bit more of a push to keep going."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Reconciliation Australia CEO says PM speech shows 'real commitment'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Djawa Yunupiŋu, brother of Yunupiŋu and leader of the Gumatj clan, has spoken to the crowds at Garma Festival, stating his support for the Voice to Parliament, Isabella Tolhurst reports. “I will be voting Yes. I will be voting for my children’s future and your children’s future, connected together on this sacred land, under the sacred stars, walking side by side”. On day one of the festival, it was announced that Djawa Yunupiŋu would become the second-ever chairman of Garma.
